title: 7. The Obturator Nerve in the Medial Compartment of the Thigh

vectorData.altText:
The obturator nerve innervates most of the muscles of the medial compartment of the thigh, and is therefore responsible for adduction of the hip.
It supplies the medial thigh with sensory fibres     .

medial to the psoas muscle. You will not see the formation of the obturator nerve because, like the femoral nerve, it is derived from the ventral rami of L2, L3 and L4 in the posterior abdominal wall.
TURN your attention back to the pelvis. Locate the obturator nerve
15.3   The Obturator Nerve in the Medial Compartment of the Thigh

Follow the obturator nerve as it skirts the pelvic brim and then passes into the obturator canal     . Gently, pass a blunt probe through the obturator canal beside the obturator nerve     . Find the tip of your probe in the medial compartment of the thigh, and use it to help you locate the obturator nerve in this compartment. It usually forms an anterior and a posterior branch.
